---
import BlogPostLayout from '../../layouts/BlogPostLayout.astro';
import { getBlogPost } from '../../lib/blog-posts';
import JaggedFrontier from '../../components/JaggedFrontier';
import JaggedSurface from '../../components/JaggedSurface';

export const frontmatter = {
  title: 'Jagged Intelligence',
  description:
    'LLMs are superhuman at some tasks and trivially bad at others. The fix is not to make them act human — it is to engineer around the surface.',
  author: 'Adelphi Liong',
  date: '2026-06-21',
  topic: 'tech' as const,
  tags: ['llm', 'ai', 'mental-models'],
  shareMessage: 'LLM capability is a jagged surface, not a ladder. Stop role-playing it human and engineer around it.',
};

const post = getBlogPost('jagged-intelligence')!;
---

<BlogPostLayout post={post}>
  <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-4 mb-6">Smart and bad at the same time</h2>

  <p class="mb-6">
    The same model that writes a clean migration in seconds will then insist that "strawberry" has two r's. Superhuman
    at some things; tripping over a task a child would get right at others.
  </p>

  <p class="mb-6">That contradiction isn't a bug to wait out. It's the most important thing to understand about these models.</p>

  <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-16 mb-6">Karpathy's jagged frontier</h2>

  <p class="mb-6">
    <strong>Andrej Karpathy</strong> named it: <strong>jagged intelligence</strong>. Capability is a jagged frontier —
    far above human ability in some directions, below trivial competence in others, all at the same "level." There's no
    single dial you turn up to raise every skill together.
  </p>

  <blockquote class="border-l-4 border-primary pl-6 py-1 my-6 italic text-muted-foreground">
    It isn't uniformly smarter than last year. It's wildly uneven — and the unevenness is the point.
  </blockquote>

  <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-16 mb-6">The ladder is the wrong picture</h2>

  <p class="mb-6">
    We default to a <strong>ladder</strong>: novice at the bottom, expert at the top, one axis. That's why "you are a
    senior staff engineer" or "respond as Warren Buffett" feel like they should work — they try to slide the model up a
    rung.
  </p>

  <p class="mb-6">
    But there's no rung to slide to. A role prompt changes tone, not arithmetic or letter-counting. Those live elsewhere
    on the shape, untouched.
  </p>

  <JaggedFrontier client:load />

  <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-16 mb-6">It's a surface, and it moves</h2>

  <p class="mb-6">
    The honest picture is a <strong>surface</strong>. Capability varies across the <strong>model</strong>, the
    <strong>input</strong>, and the <strong>task</strong> — and it doesn't track human intuition. Hard-for-us things
    (translation, recall, boilerplate) are often spikes; easy-for-us things (counting, exact math) are often dips.
  </p>

  <JaggedSurface client:load />

  <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-16 mb-6">So: engineer around it</h2>

  <p class="mb-6">
    If capability is jagged, you can't patch the dips by making the model act human. Role-play doesn't move the surface.
    Map three things instead:
  </p>

  <ul class="list-disc list-inside mb-6 space-y-2">
    <li><strong>What you're good at</strong> — judgment, taste, knowing what "done" means.</li>
    <li><strong>What it's good at</strong> — the spikes: volume, recall, transformation, tireless drafting.</li>
    <li><strong>What it's bad at</strong> — the dips: trivial-looking things it gets confidently wrong.</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="mb-6">
    Then route work along the contours: give it the spikes, keep the judgment, build scaffolding to cover the dips. Two
    disciplines grow out of this —
    <a class="text-primary hover:underline" href="/blog/autonomous-agents">Autonomous Agents</a> (the practice) and
    <a class="text-primary hover:underline" href="/blog/probability-space-engineering">Probability Space Engineering</a>
    (the theory).
  </p>

  <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-16 mb-6">Blind spots you find by watching</h2>

  <p class="mb-6">
    Worse: the dips are <strong>unpredictable</strong>. A junior fails where you expect; the model fails in places that
    feel safe. You learn a given model's blind spots only one way — <strong>watch it work</strong> on your tasks.
  </p>

  <p class="mb-6">
    So neither blanket trust nor blanket distrust is rational. Trust the mapped spikes, verify the mapped dips, and keep
    updating the map. Intelligence here isn't a height to climb — it's a shape to map.
  </p>

  <div class="mt-16 pt-8 border-t border-border">
    <p class="font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-muted-foreground mb-3">Related</p>
    <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-1 text-muted-foreground">
      <li><a class="text-primary hover:underline" href="/blog/how-llms-work">How LLMs Actually Work</a> — the mechanics under the chat box</li>
      <li><a class="text-primary hover:underline" href="/blog/autonomous-agents">Autonomous Agents</a> — working the surface in practice</li>
      <li><a class="text-primary hover:underline" href="/blog/probability-space-engineering">Probability Space Engineering</a> — the theory of shaping outputs</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</BlogPostLayout>
